          <avActivityHighlights>Gliding avalanches can also be released in the morning. Slight increase in avalanche danger as a consequence of warming during the day.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>In particular on cut and grassy slopes more small and medium-sized gliding avalanches are possible, in particular above approximately 1600 m. &lt;br/&gt; Caution is to be exercised in areas with glide cracks. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; The weather conditions will cause a slight rise in the danger of moist avalanches as the day progresses. &lt;br/&gt; Especially above approximately 2200 m: Weak layers in the old snowpack can still be released in some place by winter sport participants. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In the morning, There is a danger of falling on the hard snow surface.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>Towards its surface, the snowpack is hard and its surface has a melt-freeze crust that is strong in many cases. &lt;br/&gt; Sunshine and high temperatures will give rise from early morning to softening of the snowpack especially on sunny slopes, in the event of an overcast night in particular. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Intermediate and high altitudes: Weak layers exist in the snowpack especially on west, north and northeast facing slopes. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In particular in the vicinity of peaks snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. &lt;br/&gt;</snowpackStructureComment>
        </BulletinMeasurements>
      </bulletinResultsOf>
    </Bulletin>
